25 PART IV. PROPERTY PROTECTION ACT/DVPO
26 SECTION 4.1. G.S. 50B-3.1 reads as rewritten:
27 "§ 50B-3.1. Surrender and disposal of firearms; violations; exemptions.
28 (a) Required Surrender of Firearms. – Upon issuance of an emergency or ex parte order
29 pursuant to this Chapter, the court shall order the defendant to surrender to the sheriff all firearms,
30 machine guns, ammunition, permits to purchase firearms, and permits to carry concealed firearms
31 that are in the care, custody, possession, ownership, or control of the defendant if the court finds
32 any of the following factors:
33 (1) The use or threatened use of a deadly weapon by the defendant or a pattern of
34 prior conduct involving the use or threatened use of violence with a firearm
35 against persons.
36 (2) Threats to seriously injure or kill the aggrieved party or minor child by the
37 defendant.
38 (3) Threats to commit suicide by the defendant.
39 (4) Serious injuries inflicted upon the aggrieved party or minor child by the
40 defendant.
41 …
42 (d) Surrender. – Upon service of the order, the defendant shall immediately surrender to
43 the sheriff possession of all firearms, machine guns, ammunition, permits to purchase firearms,
44 and permits to carry concealed firearms that are in the care, custody, possession, ownership, or
45 control of the defendant. In the event that weapons cannot be surrendered at the time the order is
46 served, the defendant shall surrender the firearms, ammunitions, and permits to the sheriff within
47 24 hours of service at a time and place specified by the sheriff. The sheriff shall store the firearms
48 or contract with a licensed firearms dealer to provide storage.
49 (1) If the court orders the defendant to surrender firearms, ammunition, and
50 permits, the court shall inform the plaintiff and the defendant of the terms of
51 the protective order and include these terms on the face of the order, including
