39 PART V. AUTHORIZE THE STORAGE AND USE OF DEFENSIVE DEVICES IN
40 BIOMETRIC SAFES FOR SCHOOLS
41 SECTION 5.1. G.S. 14-269(b) reads as rewritten:
42 "(b) This prohibition shall not apply to the following persons:
43 …
44 (10) A public school unit or nonpublic school employee who meets the following
45 requirements:
46 a. The employee has completed annual training for a device
47 classification, as required by G.S. 115C-105.52, to access any
48 defensive device stored in a locked container that is securely affixed
49 to the premises of the educational property and accessible by a
50 biometric lock that limits access to only authorized employees with
Page 10 House Bill 674-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 training for defensive devices stored within the container or law
2 enforcement officers.
3 b. The employee accesses and uses a defensive device in response to a
4 threatening situation in which force was justified pursuant to
5 G.S. 14-51.3."
6 SECTION 5.2. G.S. 14-269.2(g) reads as rewritten:
7 "(g) This section shall not apply to any of the following:
8 …
9 (8) A weapon that is a defensive device stored on educational property, as
10 provided in G.S. 115C-105.52, or use of those devices by authorized
11 employees in response to a threatening situation in which force was justified
12 pursuant to G.S. 14-51.3."
13 SECTION 5.3. G.S. 115C-105.52 reads as rewritten:
14 "§ 115C-105.52. School Defensive device storage and school crisis kits.
15 (a) The following definitions apply in this section:
16 (1) Authorized employee. – An employee of a public school unit or nonpublic
17 school who meets all of the following requirements on an annual basis:
18 a. Receives training meeting the standards established by the Center for
19 Safer Schools for a device classification.
20 b. Is designated by the public school unit as an employee that may access
21 a defensive device storage container using that employee's biometric
22 information.
23 (2) Defensive device. – A device used to defend against the imminent use of
24 unlawful force. A defensive device may include, but is not limited to, a
25 disabling chemical spray, an electronic incapacitation device, or a firearm.
26 (3) Defensive device storage container. – A locked container that is securely
27 affixed to the premises of the educational property and accessible by a
28 biometric lock that limits access to only authorized employees with training
29 for any device classifications stored within the container or law enforcement
30 officers.
31 (4) Device classification. – A classification of a defensive device corresponding
32 to the required training standards established by the Center for Safer Schools
33 for use of that device by an employee of the school.
34 (5) Nonpublic school. – A school that meets the requirements of Part 1 or 2 of
35 Article 39 of this Chapter.
36 (b) Any public school unit or nonpublic school may provide for defensive devices on the
37 educational property of the school if those defensive devices are stored in a defensive device
38 storage container. The administrator for each school may affix one or more defensive device
39 storage containers at appropriate locations in the school and may post signs alerting the public to
40 the presence of the defensive device storage containers.
41 (c) No employee shall be required to complete training for any defensive device,
42 regardless of device classification. Only employees that have completed the annual training for
43 a device classification shall be eligible for biometric access to a defensive device storage
44 container with that device classification.
45 (d) A public school unit, nonpublic school, or authorized employee shall not be liable in
46 civil damages for any act or omission related to a defensive device unless the act or omission
47 amounts to gross negligence, wanton conduct, or intentional wrongdoing.
48 (e) The Center for Safer Schools, in consultation with the Department of Public
49 Instruction and the Department of Public Safety, shall develop and adopt policies on the
50 placement of school crisis kits in schools and on the contents of those kits. The kits shall include,
51 at a minimum, basic first-aid supplies and communications devices.
House Bill 674-First Edition Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (f) The principal of each school, in coordination with the law enforcement agencies that
2 are part of the public school unit's School Risk Management Plan, may place one or more crisis
3 kits at appropriate locations in the school."
4 SECTION 5.4. G.S. 143B-1209.59(c), as recodified under Section 3J.17 of S.L.
5 2024-57, reads as rewritten:
6 "(c) Powers and Duties. – The Center for Safer Schools shall have the following duties,
7 and all other powers and duties provided in Article 8C of Chapter 115C of the General Statutes:
8 …
9 (11) Establish classifications of defensive devices and, in collaboration with the
10 North Carolina Criminal Justice Education and Training Standards
11 Commission, establish minimum training standards for school employees to
12 qualify to access and use that classification of defensive device in a storage
13 container with biometric locks. The minimum training standards shall be made
14 publicly available for use of law enforcement or private entities to provide
15 training meeting those standards."
16 SECTION 5.5. Public school units awarded school safety grants for safety
17 equipment may use those grants to purchase defensive devices and defensive device storage
18 containers and associated training for public school employees.
19 SECTION 5.6. The Center for Safer Schools shall establish classifications and
20 training standards required by this section no later than January 1, 2026.
